# {{lb|en|transitive}} To furnish with dress, or [[equipment]], especially those for military service; to [[equip]].
#: {{syn|en|attire|array}}
#* '''1600''', William Shakespeare, ''Merchant of Venice, III-iv''
#*: Both '''accoutred''' like young men.
#* '''1810''', Reuben Percy and Sholto Percy, ''The Percy Anecdotes''
#*:It was therefore resolved that the king should ride on Humphrey Penderel's horse, which was taken from the grass, and '''accoutred''' with a pitiful old saddle and a worse bridle.
#* '''1814''', [[w:William Wordsworth|William Wordsworth]], ''The Excursion''
#*: Both while he trod the earth in humblest guise<br> Accoutred with his burden and his staff
#* '''6 July 2017''', Tyrel Rodricks, ''Architectural Digest India'', ''[https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/cant-take-eyes-off-bmw-8-series-concept-car/#s-cust0 We can’t take our eyes off the BMW 8 Series concept car]''
#*:The hexagonal design motifs seen around the exterior are featured extensively in the carbon-fibre and leather '''accoutred''' interiors.

